`HashMap` is not sorted. You can not rely on its order, as it is mostly `hashCode()` based.

However your problem is not related to order, it is because you are not selecting the longest prefix (the value with the highest length): if you look for 1-242, then USA (1) and Bahamas (1-242) works. Same goes for ExampleCountry (301) and Greece (30).

Your algorithm should be something like that: for each entry for which the phone number starts with the entry&#39; value, we remember the &quot;best match&quot; entry and update it whenever it was never found (initial case) or its value is bigger than previously matched.

    private static String getCountry(String telephoneNumber) {
        var bestMatch = null; // Map.Entry&lt;String,String&gt;
        for (Entry&lt;String, String&gt; entry : countriesNamesAndCodes.entrySet()){
          if (telephoneNumber.startsWith(entry.getValue()) {
            if (bestMatch == null || entry.getValue().length() &gt; bestMatch.getValue().length()) {
              bestMatch = entry;
            }
          }
        }
        return null != bestMatch ? bestMatch.getKey():null;
    }

Your code executed exactly what it was written to do, and your issue is here 
```java-lang
