```

You are extracting first search matching entry value which in your case (1-242888999) start with 1, so it will bring the entry = 1 which is USA. 

**The reason** is that you are ordering using streams in place, and when you entered the getCountry you became out of order again, so you need to save first your ordering.

Combining elements from a few of the other answers, you might want to keep a `SortedMap` from the country codes to the countries&#39; names, sorted in descending length order (with ties broken by alphabetic order).

That way, the longest match is always checked first, so you don&#39;t run into the same prefix problem.

```
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.SortedMap;
import java.util.TreeMap;
import static java.util.Map.Entry;
import static java.util.Comparator.comparingInt;
import static java.util.Comparator.naturalOrder;

class Example {
  public static void main(String[] args) {

    SortedMap&lt;String, String&gt; codeCountries = new TreeMap&lt;&gt;(
        comparingInt(String::length)
          .reversed()
          .thenComparing(naturalOrder()));

    codeCountries.putAll(Map.of(
        &quot;1&quot;, &quot;United States&quot;,
        &quot;1241&quot;, &quot;Bahamas&quot;,
    ));

    for (String name : codeCountries.values) {
        System.out.println(name);
        // Prints &quot;United States&quot;, then &quot;Bahamas&quot;
    }
  }
}
```

The only other change you would need would be that you would have to remove the dashes from the country codes _before_ putting them in the map. If you don&#39;t, both keys will remain in the map.

As a similar, potentially faster (but not so much faster that it would really matter) alternative, you could keep a non-sorted map with the country codes as its keys, and whenever you get an input, you could try getting all of its prefixes from the map:

```
Map&lt;String, String&gt; countryCodes = Map.of(&quot;1242&quot;, &quot;Bahamas&quot;, &quot;1&quot;, &quot;United States&quot;);

String input = /* get some input */;

for (int i = input.length; i &gt; 0; --i) {
    String country = countryCodes.get(input.substring(0, i));
    if (country != null) {
        return country;
    }
}
// If you get here, no country code was found in the map.

// Alternatively, with streams:
IntStream.range(0, input.length())
  .mapToObj(i -&gt; input.substring(0, input.length() - i))
  .filter(countryCodes::containsKey)
  .findFirst();
```

However, a more reliable idea than worrying about parsing country codes or detecting overlap between them (especially if your users sometimes forget to include their country code) would be to ask for the country code first, then the rest of the number. Then you could just look up the country code directly, without worrying about overlaps.

